=========================================================
std::weak_ptr (C++11) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================================

1. What is std::weak_ptr?
-------------------------
- A smart pointer introduced in C++11.
- It is a NON-OWNING smart pointer.
- It works with std::shared_ptr.
- It does NOT increase reference count.
- Used to break circular dependency.

Header:
#include <memory>

Interview Line:
"weak_ptr observes an object managed by shared_ptr without owning it."

=========================================================
2. Why weak_ptr is needed?
--------------------------
Problem: Circular dependency with shared_ptr

Example:

A -> B (shared_ptr)
B -> A (shared_ptr)

Reference count never becomes 0 → MEMORY LEAK

Solution:
✔ Use weak_ptr to break the cycle

=========================================================
Circular Dependency Problem with shared_ptr (MOST ASKED)
=========================================================

Code:

class B;

class A
{
public:
    shared_ptr<B> bptr;
};

class B
{
public:
    shared_ptr<A> aptr;
};

int main()
{
    shared_ptr<A> a = make_shared<A>();
    shared_ptr<B> b = make_shared<B>();

    a->bptr = b;
    b->aptr = a;
}

=========================================================
Step 1: Create Objects
=========================================================

shared_ptr<A> a = make_shared<A>();
shared_ptr<B> b = make_shared<B>();

Reference Counts:

A count = 1
B count = 1

because:

a owns A
b owns B

=========================================================
Step 2: Assign shared_ptr
=========================================================

Initially:

shared_ptr<A> a = make_shared<A>();
shared_ptr<B> b = make_shared<B>();

Memory:

a ------> A
b ------> B

Reference counts:

A count = 1
B count = 1

because:

a owns A
b owns B

=========================================================
Now execute:
=========================================================

a->bptr = b;

This means:

A object's member bptr now COPIES the shared_ptr b.

Equivalent to:

A.bptr = b;

Since shared_ptr copy constructor is called,
ownership is SHARED.

Before:

b ------> B

After:

b --------\
           \
            -----> B
           /
A.bptr ---/

Now there are TWO owners of B:

1. b
2. a->bptr

Therefore:

B count = 2

because:

b owns B
a->bptr also owns B

---------------------------------------------------------

b->aptr = a;

A count becomes:

A count = 2

because:

a owns A
b->aptr also owns A

Final counts:

A count = 2
B count = 2

=========================================================
Memory Diagram
=========================================================

a ------> A
            |
            | shared_ptr<B>
            v
            B
            ^
            |
            | shared_ptr<A>
            |
b ----------+

Or simply:

A <--------> B
(shared ownership both ways)

=========================================================
Step 3: End of main()
=========================================================

Local variables are destroyed.

a destroyed:

A count: 2 -> 1

b destroyed:

B count: 2 -> 1

Final counts:

A count = 1
B count = 1

Neither becomes zero.

Therefore:

~A() NOT called
~B() NOT called
Heap memory NOT freed
Memory leak occurs.

=========================================================
Why does this happen?
=========================================================

A owns B.
B owns A.

Both objects keep each other alive.

Each object is waiting for the other's reference count
to become zero, which never happens.

This is called:

1. Circular Dependency
2. Circular Reference
3. Cyclic Ownership

=========================================================
Is it an Infinite Loop?
=========================================================

NO.

=========================================================
Does Program Crash?
=========================================================

NO.

=========================================================
Does Program Hang?
=========================================================

NO.

=========================================================
What Actually Happens?
=========================================================

Program exits normally.

But:

A object remains on heap.
B object remains on heap.
Destructors are never called.
Memory leak occurs.

=========================================================
How to Fix?
=========================================================

Make one side weak_ptr.

class B
{
public:
    weak_ptr<A> aptr;
};

Now:

A count = 1
B count = 2

At end of main():

a destroyed
A count: 1 -> 0
A object deleted

A's bptr destroyed
B count: 2 -> 1

b destroyed
B count: 1 -> 0
B object deleted

No memory leak.

=========================================================
Interview One-Line Answer
=========================================================

The problem is circular ownership. Both A and B hold
shared_ptr to each other, so their reference counts never
become zero. As a result, destructors are never called and
both objects leak memory. The solution is to replace one of
the shared_ptr objects with weak_ptr because weak_ptr does
not participate in ownership or increase the shared
reference count.
=========================================================

=========================================================
4. Fix using weak_ptr
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

class B;

class A
{
public:
    shared_ptr<B> bptr;
};

class B
{
public:
    weak_ptr<A> aptr;   // FIX: weak_ptr
};

int main()
{
    shared_ptr<A> a = make_shared<A>();
    shared_ptr<B> b = make_shared<B>();

    a->bptr = b;
    b->aptr = a;   // does NOT increase reference count

    cout << "No memory leak now\n";
}

=========================================================
5. How weak_ptr Works Internally
=========================================================

weak_ptr:
• Points to shared object
• Does NOT increase reference count
• Uses control block of shared_ptr

It has:
- weak reference to control block
- does NOT own memory

=========================================================
6. Key Methods of weak_ptr
=========================================================

1. use_count()
----------------
Returns shared_ptr reference count

2. expired()
------------
Returns true if object is already deleted

3. lock()
---------
Converts weak_ptr → shared_ptr (if object exists)

=========================================================
7. Example: lock()
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    shared_ptr<int> sp = make_shared<int>(10);
    weak_ptr<int> wp = sp;

    cout << "use_count: " << wp.use_count() << endl;

    if(auto temp = wp.lock())   // convert to shared_ptr
    {
        cout << "Value: " << *temp << endl;
    }
    else
    {
        cout << "Object already deleted\n";
    }
}

=========================================================
8. Example: expired()
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <memory>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    weak_ptr<int> wp;

    {
        shared_ptr<int> sp = make_shared<int>(20);
        wp = sp;

        cout << wp.expired() << endl; // 0 (false)
    }

    cout << wp.expired() << endl;     // 1 (true)
}

=========================================================
9. weak_ptr vs shared_ptr
=========================================================

Feature              shared_ptr              weak_ptr
---------------------------------------------------------------
Ownership            YES                     NO
Reference Count      INCREASES               DOES NOT increase
Can delete object    YES (last owner)        NO
Access object        Direct                  Only via lock()
Use case             Shared ownership        Observer / break cycles

=========================================================
10. When to use weak_ptr?
-------------------------
✔ Break circular references
✔ Cache systems
✔ Observer patterns
✔ Temporary access to shared resource
✔ Avoid ownership

=========================================================
11. Important Safety Rule
-------------------------
Never dereference weak_ptr directly.

Wrong:
    *wp   ❌

Correct:
    auto sp = wp.lock();

=========================================================
12. REAL WORLD EXAMPLE
=========================================================

Cache system:

class Cache
{
    weak_ptr<Data> data;
};

If data still exists → reuse it
Else → reload

=========================================================
13. ONE-LINE INTERVIEW ANSWER
=========================================================

std::weak_ptr is a smart pointer that observes an object managed by
std::shared_ptr without owning it. It does not increase reference count
and is mainly used to break circular dependencies and avoid memory leaks.

